Conditional aggregates with filter.

Sometimes you want to aggregate only the rows that match a condition, and aggregate over a different condition in the same row, all in one pass. The standard sequel feature for this is filter, with a where inside, attached to an aggregate call. For example: sum of amount, filter where order date is on or after a given day.

This is dramatically cleaner than the old idiom of summing a case expression, and it lets the engine optimize more aggressively. It is supported by Postgres, DuckDB, Sequelite, and Snowflake. Sequel server and MySQL still require the case form.

It is the right tool when you want side-by-side aggregates over different slices of the same rows, for instance this-period versus prior-period totals in a single row.
